  <section>
    <h2>Business Scenario</h2>

    <p>
      A mid-sized organization is establishing its first AWS networking foundation
      to support modern cloud-hosted applications. The initial requirement is to
      create a secure, scalable network design that separates internet-facing
      services from internal workloads while leaving room for future growth.
    </p>

    <p>
      The environment must follow cloud architecture best practices, be fully
      documented, and be deployable through Infrastructure as Code (IaC) so it can
      be repeated consistently across future development, testing, and production
      environments.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section>
  <h2>Requirements</h2>

  <h3>Business Requirements</h3>
  <p>The networking foundation must:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Support both internet-facing and internal application workloads.</li>
    <li>Separate public and private resources to improve security.</li>
    <li>Be scalable to accommodate future environments such as development, testing, and production.</li>
    <li>Be reproducible through Infrastructure as Code (IaC).</li>
    <li>Follow AWS networking best practices.</li>
    <li>Provide a maintainable foundation for future cloud services.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Technical Requirements</h3>
  <p>The solution must include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A dedicated Amazon VPC.</li>
    <li>Public and private subnets.</li>
    <li>Route tables for controlled traffic flow.</li>
    <li>An Internet Gateway for public internet access.</li>
    <li>Security groups to control inbound and outbound traffic.</li>
    <li>CIDR planning that allows future network expansion.</li>
    <li>Deployment using Terraform.</li>
    <li>Documentation that clearly explains both the implementation and the architectural decisions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Constraints and Assumptions</h3>
  <p>For this foundational case study:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The environment is deployed within a single AWS Region.</li>
    <li>IPv4 addressing is used throughout the implementation.</li>
    <li>Cost optimization is considered by limiting resources to those required for learning and validation.</li>
    <li>The environment is intended as a clean-room demonstration rather than a production deployment.</li>
    <li>Resources can be safely destroyed and recreated through Terraform as needed.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Architecture Overview</h2>

  <p>
    This architecture establishes a dedicated Amazon VPC as the networking
    foundation for cloud-hosted workloads. The VPC provides an isolated network
    boundary where subnets, routing, and security controls can be designed
    intentionally rather than relying on default AWS networking resources.
  </p>

  <p>
    The network is divided into public and private subnets. Their routing
    behavior—not their names—determines their network reachability. The public
    subnet is associated with a route table that directs default traffic to the
    Internet Gateway, while the private subnet is associated with a route table
    that contains only the VPC local route.
  </p>

  <p>
    An Internet Gateway is attached to the VPC to support internet connectivity
    for the public subnet. Route tables are used to control how traffic moves
    between the subnets, the VPC, and the internet. Security groups provide an
    additional layer of traffic control at the resource level.
  </p>

  <p>
    The environment is deployed with Terraform so the network can be created,
    reviewed, destroyed, and recreated consistently. This supports repeatable
    deployments and provides a documented foundation for future enhancements
    such as NAT Gateways, multi-AZ expansion, VPC peering, and additional
    workload tiers.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Routing Architecture</h2>

  <p>
    The public and private subnets are explicitly associated with separate
    route tables. Both route tables contain the AWS-provided local route for
    the VPC CIDR, allowing permitted communication between resources inside
    the VPC.
  </p>

  <p>
    The public route table also contains a default route
    (<code>0.0.0.0/0</code>) whose target is the Internet Gateway. This route
    gives resources in the public subnet a path to external IPv4 destinations
    when public addressing and resource-level security controls are also
    configured appropriately.
  </p>

  <p>
    The private route table intentionally contains no default route to the
    Internet Gateway. Resources placed in the private subnet therefore have no
    direct internet path while retaining internal VPC connectivity through the
    local route.
  </p>

  <p>
    This separation demonstrates an important AWS networking principle:
    subnets define network boundaries, while route tables determine where
    traffic can be directed. Security groups then determine whether that
    traffic is permitted at the resource level.
  </p>
</section>

