<section>
  <h2>Key Design Decisions</h2>

  <h3>Building a Dedicated VPC</h3>

  <p>
    Rather than modifying the default AWS VPC, this architecture creates a
    dedicated Virtual Private Cloud. A dedicated VPC provides complete control
    over IP addressing, routing, security boundaries, and future expansion while
    avoiding dependencies on AWS default resources. This approach more closely
    reflects enterprise cloud deployments.
  </p>

  <h3>Separating Public and Private Subnets</h3>

  <p>
    Resources requiring internet connectivity are placed in public subnets,
    while internal workloads are isolated within private subnets. Separating
    these network tiers reduces the attack surface and follows AWS networking
    best practices by limiting direct internet exposure.
  </p>

  <h3>CIDR Planning</h3>

  <p>
    IP address ranges were selected to provide room for future subnet growth
    without requiring network redesign. Thoughtful CIDR planning simplifies
    expansion into additional Availability Zones and supports future application
    environments such as development, testing, and production.
  </p>

  <h3>Infrastructure as Code</h3>

  <p>
    Terraform is used to define the networking infrastructure as code rather
    than creating resources manually through the AWS Management Console. This
    enables consistent deployments, version control, peer review, and rapid
    recreation of the environment when changes are required.
  </p>

  <h3>Architecture as Code</h3>

  <p>
    Architecture diagrams are maintained as version-controlled Mermaid source
    and rendered into reusable SVG assets. Supporting implementation notes and
    design decisions are maintained as Markdown documentation alongside the
    Terraform code, keeping the complete engineering record synchronized with
    the infrastructure.
  </p>
</section>

