<section>
  <h2>Lessons Learned</h2>

  <p>
    Building this networking foundation reinforced that successful cloud
    architecture depends as much on thoughtful planning as it does on technical
    implementation. Designing the network before deploying resources resulted
    in a cleaner, more scalable architecture and highlighted the importance of
    making intentional design decisions early in the project lifecycle.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      Careful CIDR planning simplifies future expansion and helps avoid
      unnecessary network redesign.
    </li>

    <li>
      Public and private subnet separation provides a clear security boundary
      and establishes a foundation for layered network security.
    </li>

    <li>
      Infrastructure as Code makes cloud environments repeatable, consistent,
      and significantly easier to maintain than manual deployments.
    </li>

    <li>
      Architecture diagrams and documentation are valuable engineering assets,
      not simply project deliverables. Keeping them synchronized with the
      infrastructure improves maintainability and communication.
    </li>

    <li>
      Small architectural decisions made early in a project can significantly
      influence future scalability, security, and operational simplicity.
    </li>
    <li>
      A subnet becomes public through its route-table association and a default
      route to an Internet Gateway; the subnet name alone does not determine its
      reachability.
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

